[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 7.4: ED Visit Prediction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.02 per patient scored per month
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's a number that should bother you: the average emergency department visit costs somewhere between $1,500 and $3,000. For a health plan with 500,000 members, even a 5% reduction in avoidable ED visits translates to tens of millions in savings per year. For a health system, those same visits represent overcrowded departments, burned-out staff, and patients waiting six hours for something that could have been handled in a primary care office three days earlier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The frustrating part is that many of these visits are predictable. Not all of them. A car accident is not predictable. A sudden cardiac event is not predictable. But the patient with poorly controlled diabetes who hasn't seen their PCP in eight months and just ran out of insulin? That ED visit is coming. The COPD patient who missed their last two pulmonary rehab appointments and whose pharmacy claims show they stopped filling their maintenance inhaler? That one's coming too.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pattern is almost always the same: a slow accumulation of risk factors (missed appointments, medication gaps, worsening lab values, social instability) followed by an acute crisis that lands in the ED. The window between "this patient is drifting" and "this patient is in the emergency room" is typically 30 to 90 days. That's your intervention window. If you can identify who's drifting before they crash, you can deploy care management resources: outreach calls, medication reconciliation, transportation assistance, urgent PCP appointments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge is that you're not just predicting who will visit the ED. You're predicting who will visit the ED for a reason that was preventable with earlier intervention. That distinction is everything. A model that flags patients who are about to have a stroke is interesting but not actionable in the same way. You need to identify the patients where a phone call, a home visit, or a same-day clinic slot would have changed the outcome.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is one of those problems where the ML is actually the easy part. The hard part is building the operational infrastructure to act on the predictions before they expire.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Predicting Emergency Utilization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What We're Actually Predicting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's be precise about the prediction target, because getting this wrong is the most common failure mode in ED prediction projects.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You're building a model that answers: "For each patient in my population, what is the probability that they will have an emergency department visit in the next 30 to 90 days?" But that's the naive version. The useful version adds a qualifier: "...for a reason that could have been prevented or redirected with proactive outreach."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This distinction matters because it changes your training data. If you train on all ED visits, your model will learn to predict trauma, heart attacks, and strokes. Those are high-signal events (prior cardiac history strongly predicts future cardiac events), but they're not actionable in the same way. You want to predict ambulatory care sensitive conditions (ACSCs): asthma exacerbations, diabetic crises, COPD flares, urinary tract infections that became sepsis, mental health crises. These are the visits where earlier intervention could have changed the trajectory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The AHRQ (Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality) maintains a well-established list of Prevention Quality Indicators (PQIs) that define which conditions are considered ambulatory care sensitive. Your outcome label should be filtered to these conditions, or a locally adapted version of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Feature Space
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ED visit prediction is a classic tabular ML problem. You're combining features from multiple data domains into a single patient-level feature vector and training a supervised classifier. The feature categories that matter most:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior utilization.** The single strongest predictor of future ED use is past ED use. Patients with two or more ED visits in the prior 12 months are dramatically more likely to have another one. This is not a sophisticated insight, but it's the baseline your model needs to beat. Beyond raw counts, look at recency (days since last ED visit), frequency patterns, and the trajectory (increasing vs. stable vs. decreasing).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical complexity.** Chronic condition burden, measured by something like the Charlson Comorbidity Index or HCC (Hierarchical Condition Category) risk scores. Patients with multiple interacting chronic conditions are harder to manage and more likely to decompensate. Specific conditions matter more than others: COPD, heart failure, diabetes, and serious mental illness are the big four for avoidable ED use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care engagement signals.** This is where the model gets interesting. Missed appointments, gaps in preventive care, medication non-adherence (measured by pharmacy fill gaps), and time since last PCP visit are all leading indicators. A patient who was engaged and is becoming disengaged is a different risk profile than a patient who was never engaged.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social and behavioral factors.** This is also where the model gets hard. Transportation barriers, housing instability, food insecurity, and social isolation all drive ED utilization. The problem is that this data is rarely structured, rarely complete, and rarely in your claims or EHR system. Some organizations use area-level proxies (Area Deprivation Index, census tract characteristics), which are better than nothing but introduce ecological fallacy risks. Others use SDOH screening data when available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pharmacy data.** Medication possession ratio (MPR) and proportion of days covered (PDC) are standard adherence metrics calculated from pharmacy claims. A patient whose PDC for their diabetes medication drops below 80% is signaling trouble. Polypharmacy (many concurrent medications) also correlates with ED risk, partly because of drug interaction risks and partly because complex regimens are harder to maintain.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal patterns.** Seasonality matters. Respiratory conditions spike in winter. Mental health crises have seasonal patterns. Day-of-week and time-of-day patterns in prior visits can signal whether a patient uses the ED as a primary care substitute (weekday evening visits for non-urgent complaints) versus genuine emergencies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Model Architecture Choices
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For tabular prediction problems with structured features, gradient boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost) remain the dominant approach. They handle mixed feature types naturally, are robust to missing values (common in healthcare data), and produce well-calibrated probabilities when properly tuned. They also offer feature importance scores that are critical for clinical interpretability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Deep learning approaches (neural networks) can work here but rarely outperform gradient boosted trees on structured tabular data, and they sacrifice interpretability. The exception is when you have sequential data (time-ordered event sequences) where recurrent architectures or transformers can capture temporal patterns that flat feature vectors miss.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Logistic regression is worth mentioning because it's still used in many production healthcare risk models (LACE score, HOSPITAL score). It's fully interpretable, easy to validate, and clinically trusted. If your organization is deploying its first predictive model and clinician buy-in is the primary concern, logistic regression with well-chosen features may be the right starting point even if it sacrifices a few points of AUC.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Calibration: The Thing Everyone Forgets
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's where most ED prediction projects go wrong: they optimize for discrimination (AUC, the ability to rank patients by risk) and forget about calibration (whether a predicted probability of 30% actually means 30% of those patients will visit the ED).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Calibration matters because your downstream workflow depends on it. If you're allocating care management resources, you need to know: "If I intervene on the top 5% of patients by predicted risk, how many ED visits will I actually prevent?" That calculation requires calibrated probabilities, not just a ranking.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Platt scaling or isotonic regression applied after model training can fix calibration without sacrificing discrimination. Always plot calibration curves (predicted probability vs. observed frequency) as part of your model evaluation. A model with AUC of 0.78 and good calibration is more useful than a model with AUC of 0.82 and terrible calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Fairness Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ED prediction models trained on historical data will encode historical disparities. Patients from underserved communities have higher ED utilization partly because they face barriers to primary care access (transportation, clinic hours, insurance coverage, implicit bias). A model trained on this data will correctly predict that these patients are high-risk, but the intervention ("call them and offer a PCP appointment") may not address the actual barrier ("they can't get to the clinic because they work two jobs and have no car").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This isn't a reason not to build the model. It's a reason to be thoughtful about what you do with the predictions. Fairness auditing across demographic groups (race, ethnicity, age, geography, insurance type) should be part of your model evaluation pipeline. If the model performs significantly worse for certain subgroups, or if interventions are less effective for certain subgroups, that's a signal to investigate the root cause rather than just recalibrate the scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Data Integration] → [Feature Engineering] → [Model Training] → [Scoring Pipeline] → [Risk Stratification] → [Intervention Routing]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data Integration.** Pull claims, EHR encounters, pharmacy fills, lab results, and (if available) SDOH data into a unified patient-level dataset. This is typically the hardest engineering step. Healthcare data lives in silos, uses inconsistent identifiers, and arrives on different cadences (claims lag 30-90 days; EHR data is near-real-time).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Engineering.** Transform raw events into patient-level features: rolling counts, time-since calculations, trend indicators, adherence ratios. The feature engineering step is where domain expertise matters most. A data scientist who understands that "days since last PCP visit" and "number of specialist visits without a PCP visit" tell different clinical stories will build a better model than one who just throws everything in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model Training.** Train a supervised classifier on historical data where the outcome is "ED visit within N days for an ACSC condition." Use time-based train/test splits (train on 2022-2023, validate on early 2024, test on late 2024) to avoid data leakage. Never use random splits for temporal prediction problems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Scoring Pipeline.** Run the trained model against the current population on a regular cadence (daily or weekly). Each patient gets a risk score and a set of contributing factors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Risk Stratification.** Divide the scored population into actionable tiers: high risk (immediate outreach), rising risk (monitor closely), moderate risk (standard care management), low risk (no action). The tier thresholds should be calibrated to your care management capacity. There's no point flagging 10,000 patients as high-risk if you have capacity to call 200 per week.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intervention Routing.** Route high-risk patients to the appropriate intervention: care manager outreach, pharmacy consultation, transportation assistance, urgent PCP scheduling. The routing logic should consider the primary risk drivers for each patient, not just the overall score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and hosting.** SageMaker provides the full ML lifecycle: data preparation, training, hyperparameter tuning, model hosting, and batch inference. For a gradient boosted tree model on tabular data, you'll use the built-in XGBoost algorithm or bring your own training container. SageMaker's batch transform is particularly useful here because ED prediction is a batch scoring problem (score the entire population weekly), not a real-time inference problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue for data integration and feature engineering.** Healthcare data integration is an ETL-heavy problem. Claims data, EHR extracts, pharmacy feeds, and eligibility files arrive in different formats on different schedules. Glue handles the extraction, transformation, and loading into a unified feature store. Glue's Spark-based engine handles the scale (millions of patients, billions of claims) without you managing infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake storage.** Raw data lands in S3. Transformed features live in S3. Model artifacts live in S3. Training datasets live in S3. It's the gravity well for everything in this pipeline. Organize with a clear prefix structure: `raw/`, `curated/`, `features/`, `models/`, `scores/`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Athena for ad-hoc analysis and model monitoring.** Once your features and scores are in S3 (Parquet format), Athena lets you query them with SQL without spinning up infrastructure. This is invaluable for model monitoring: "What's the distribution of scores this week vs. last week? Are we seeing drift in the pharmacy adherence features?"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for orchestration.** The scoring pipeline runs on a schedule (weekly or daily). EventBridge triggers the pipeline, which runs through Glue for feature refresh, SageMaker batch transform for scoring, and a Lambda function for risk stratification and routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for risk stratification and notification.** After batch scoring produces raw probabilities, a Lambda function applies tier thresholds, generates the intervention worklist, and pushes notifications to the care management platform. Lambda is right-sized for this: it's a short-lived computation that runs after each scoring batch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for the intervention worklist.** Care managers need a queryable, real-time view of their assigned patients and risk scores. DynamoDB provides fast lookups by care manager ID, patient ID, or risk tier. It also supports TTL for automatic expiration of stale scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Data Sources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A[Claims Data\nS3 raw/claims/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         B[EHR Extracts\nS3 raw/ehr/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         C[Pharmacy Feeds\nS3 raw/pharmacy/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         D[Eligibility Files\nS3 raw/eligibility/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Feature Pipeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         E[AWS Glue\nETL + Feature Engineering]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         F[S3 Feature Store\nfeatures/patient_vectors/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph ML Pipeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         G[SageMaker Training\nXGBoost]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         H[SageMaker Batch Transform\nWeekly Scoring]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         I[S3 Scores\nscores/weekly/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Action Layer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         J[Lambda\nRisk Stratification]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         K[DynamoDB\nIntervention Worklist]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L[Care Management\nPlatform]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A --> E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B --> E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C --> E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D --> E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F --> G
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F --> H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Model Artifact| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H --> I
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I --> J
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K --> L
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M[EventBridge\nWeekly Schedule] -->|Trigger| E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M -->|Trigger| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style K fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, AWS Glue, Amazon S3, Amazon Athena, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon EventBridge |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateTransformJob`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `lambda:InvokeFunction` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: patient claims and clinical data are PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); SageMaker: KMS for training volumes and model artifacts; all data in transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker training and batch transform in VPC with no internet access; VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker API, CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all SageMaker, Glue, and S3 API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Data Requirements** | Minimum 12-24 months of historical claims, pharmacy, and encounter data. Larger history improves temporal feature quality. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | CMS Synthetic Public Use Files (SynPUFs) provide realistic claims data for development. Never use real PHI in dev/test environments. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Glue ETL: ~$50/run for 1M patients; SageMaker training: ~$20/run (ml.m5.xlarge, 2 hours); Batch transform: ~$15/run; Storage and DynamoDB: ~$30/month. Total: ~$200/month for weekly scoring of 500K patients. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Model training (XGBoost), hyperparameter tuning, batch scoring |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL from raw data sources, feature engineering at scale |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for raw data, features, model artifacts, and scores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | Ad-hoc queries for model monitoring and feature analysis |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Intervention worklist for care management teams |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Risk stratification logic, notification routing |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Pipeline orchestration on weekly schedule |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing resources |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Pipeline monitoring, scoring job metrics, drift alerts |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): Comprehensive SageMaker examples including XGBoost for tabular classification, batch transform, and model monitoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`aws-healthcare-lifescience-ai-ml`](https://github.com/aws-samples/aws-healthcare-lifescience-ai-ml): Healthcare-specific ML examples on AWS including patient risk prediction patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Data integration and patient timeline assembly.** Before you can engineer features, you need a unified view of each patient's history. Claims, pharmacy fills, encounters, and eligibility data arrive in different formats with different identifiers. This step pulls them together into a single patient-keyed timeline. The timeline is the foundation for everything downstream: every feature is derived from it. Skip this step or do it poorly, and your features will be incomplete, your model will underperform, and you won't know why.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION build_patient_timeline(claims_path, pharmacy_path, ehr_path, eligibility_path):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load raw data from each source system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each source uses slightly different patient identifiers and date formats.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     claims      = load_parquet(claims_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pharmacy    = load_parquet(pharmacy_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     encounters  = load_parquet(ehr_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     eligibility = load_parquet(eligibility_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Resolve patient identity across sources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Claims use member_id, EHR uses MRN, pharmacy uses a third identifier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The eligibility file is typically the rosetta stone that maps between them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_crosswalk = build_crosswalk(eligibility)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Standardize each source to a common schema:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // { patient_id, event_type, event_date, event_details }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     unified_events = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each claim in claims:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append { patient_id: crosswalk.resolve(claim.member_id),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  event_type: "claim",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  event_date: claim.service_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  details: { diagnosis_codes: claim.dx_codes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             procedure_codes: claim.proc_codes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             place_of_service: claim.pos,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             allowed_amount: claim.allowed } }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each fill in pharmacy:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append { patient_id: crosswalk.resolve(fill.member_id),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  event_type: "pharmacy_fill",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  event_date: fill.fill_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  details: { ndc: fill.ndc_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             days_supply: fill.days_supply,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             quantity: fill.quantity } }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each encounter in encounters:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append { patient_id: crosswalk.resolve(encounter.mrn),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  event_type: "encounter",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  event_date: encounter.encounter_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  details: { encounter_type: encounter.type,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             provider_id: encounter.provider,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             diagnoses: encounter.dx_list } }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sort by patient and date. This ordering is critical for temporal features.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     unified_events = sort by (patient_id, event_date)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write to the curated layer for feature engineering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write_parquet(unified_events, "s3://bucket/curated/patient_timelines/")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN unified_events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Feature engineering.** This is where domain expertise earns its keep. You're transforming a raw event timeline into a fixed-width feature vector that captures the patient's current state, recent trajectory, and historical patterns. The features fall into categories: utilization counts, recency measures, adherence ratios, clinical complexity scores, and engagement signals. Each feature should have a clear clinical hypothesis behind it ("patients who miss appointments are disengaging from care, which precedes ED visits"). Features without a clinical rationale tend to be noise or proxies for confounders.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION engineer_features(patient_timeline, scoring_date):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define lookback windows. Different features need different time horizons.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Recent behavior (30-90 days) captures current trajectory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Longer history (12 months) captures baseline patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     window_30d  = scoring_date - 30 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     window_90d  = scoring_date - 90 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     window_180d = scoring_date - 180 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     window_12m  = scoring_date - 365 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = {}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Utilization features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Prior ED use is the single strongest predictor. Capture count and recency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["ed_visits_12m"]     = count events where type="claim" AND pos="emergency" AND date > window_12m
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["ed_visits_90d"]     = count events where type="claim" AND pos="emergency" AND date > window_90d
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["days_since_last_ed"] = days between scoring_date and most recent ED claim (or 999 if none)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Inpatient admissions signal clinical instability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["inpatient_admits_12m"] = count events where type="claim" AND pos="inpatient" AND date > window_12m
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // PCP visits signal engagement. Absence signals disengagement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["pcp_visits_12m"]       = count events where type="encounter" AND encounter_type="office_visit_pcp" AND date > window_12m
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["days_since_last_pcp"]  = days between scoring_date and most recent PCP visit (or 999 if none)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Specialist visits without PCP visits may indicate fragmented care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["specialist_visits_12m"] = count events where type="encounter" AND encounter_type="specialist" AND date > window_12m
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Engagement features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Missed appointments are a leading indicator of disengagement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["missed_appts_90d"] = count events where type="encounter" AND status="no_show" AND date > window_90d
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Medication adherence features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Calculate Proportion of Days Covered (PDC) for key medication classes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // PDC below 80% is the standard threshold for non-adherence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["pdc_diabetes_meds"]     = calculate_pdc(pharmacy_events, class="antidiabetic", window=window_180d, end=scoring_date)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["pdc_respiratory_meds"]  = calculate_pdc(pharmacy_events, class="respiratory", window=window_180d, end=scoring_date)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["pdc_cardiac_meds"]      = calculate_pdc(pharmacy_events, class="cardiac", window=window_180d, end=scoring_date)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["active_medications"]    = count distinct NDCs with active supply as of scoring_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Clinical complexity features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Chronic condition burden. More conditions = more opportunities for decompensation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["hcc_risk_score"]        = calculate_hcc_score(claims in window_12m)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["chronic_condition_count"] = count distinct chronic condition categories from dx codes in window_12m
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["has_diabetes"]          = 1 if any diabetes dx in window_12m else 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["has_copd"]              = 1 if any COPD dx in window_12m else 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["has_chf"]               = 1 if any heart failure dx in window_12m else 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["has_mental_health_dx"]  = 1 if any mental health dx in window_12m else 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Demographic and social features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["age"]                   = patient age as of scoring_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["area_deprivation_index"] = ADI score for patient's census tract (proxy for SDOH)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Temporal trend features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Is utilization increasing or decreasing? Trajectory matters more than level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["ed_trend"] = (ed_visits in last 90 days) - (ed_visits in prior 90 days)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["pdc_trend"] = (avg PDC last 90 days) - (avg PDC prior 90 days)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Model training with temporal validation.** Train a gradient boosted tree classifier on historical data. The critical detail here is the validation strategy: you must use time-based splits, not random splits. Random splits allow future information to leak into training data (a patient's January features could be in training while their March outcome is in the test set from a different random draw). Time-based splits simulate how the model will actually be used: trained on the past, predicting the future.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION train_ed_prediction_model(feature_dataset):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define temporal splits. Never use random splits for prediction problems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The model should only ever see the past when making predictions about the future.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     train_data = features where scoring_date < "2024-07-01"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     valid_data = features where scoring_date >= "2024-07-01" AND scoring_date < "2024-10-01"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     test_data  = features where scoring_date >= "2024-10-01"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define the outcome label.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 1 = patient had an ED visit for an ambulatory care sensitive condition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //     within 90 days of the scoring date.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 0 = no such visit occurred.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Filter to AHRQ PQI conditions only. This is the "avoidable" filter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     train_labels = label_ed_visits(train_data, horizon_days=90, condition_filter="AHRQ_PQI")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Configure XGBoost for binary classification with probability output.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model_params = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         objective:        "binary:logistic",   // output calibrated probabilities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         eval_metric:      "auc",               // optimize for discrimination
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         max_depth:        6,                   // limit tree depth to reduce overfitting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         learning_rate:    0.05,                // slow learning for better generalization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         n_estimators:     500,                 // enough trees for the learning rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         subsample:        0.8,                 // row sampling for regularization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         colsample_bytree: 0.8,                // column sampling for regularization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scale_pos_weight: (count negatives / count positives),  // handle class imbalance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         early_stopping_rounds: 20             // stop if validation metric plateaus
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Train the model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model = train XGBoost classifier with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         training_data   = train_data features + train_labels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         validation_data = valid_data features + valid_labels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         parameters      = model_params
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Evaluate on held-out test set.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     test_predictions = model.predict_probability(test_data)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     metrics = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         auc:         calculate_auc(test_labels, test_predictions),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         calibration: calculate_brier_score(test_labels, test_predictions),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         precision_at_5pct: precision at top 5% of predictions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         recall_at_5pct:    recall at top 5% of predictions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply calibration correction (Platt scaling) to improve probability accuracy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     calibrator = fit_platt_scaling(valid_labels, model.predict_probability(valid_data))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model.calibrator = calibrator
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save model artifact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_model(model, "s3://bucket/models/ed_prediction/latest/")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN model, metrics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Batch scoring.** Run the trained model against the current population on a weekly cadence. Every active member gets a risk score. The output is a scored population file that feeds the risk stratification step. Weekly scoring balances freshness (catching patients whose risk is rising) against computational cost and data latency (claims data is typically 2-4 weeks behind).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION score_population(model_path, current_features_path, scoring_date):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the trained model and current feature vectors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model    = load_model(model_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = load_parquet(current_features_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Score every active patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The output is a calibrated probability: "likelihood of avoidable ED visit in next 90 days."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     scores = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient in features:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         raw_probability = model.predict_probability(patient.feature_vector)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         calibrated_probability = model.calibrator.transform(raw_probability)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Extract top contributing features for this patient's score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // These drive the intervention strategy: if medication adherence is the top driver,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // the intervention is pharmacy outreach, not a PCP appointment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         top_drivers = get_shap_values(model, patient.feature_vector, top_n=5)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scores.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:    patient.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             score:         calibrated_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             score_date:    scoring_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             risk_drivers:  top_drivers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model_version: model.version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write scores to S3 for downstream consumption.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write_parquet(scores, "s3://bucket/scores/weekly/{scoring_date}/")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN scores
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Risk stratification and intervention routing.** Raw scores become actionable when you apply tier thresholds calibrated to your care management capacity. A score of 0.42 means nothing to a care manager. "High risk, primary driver is medication non-adherence, recommended action is pharmacy outreach" is actionable. This step translates model output into operational decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Tier thresholds calibrated to care management capacity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // These are not universal. Calibrate to YOUR team's bandwidth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m HIGH_RISK_THRESHOLD    = 0.35   // top ~3% of population
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m RISING_RISK_THRESHOLD  = 0.20   // next ~7%
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m MODERATE_THRESHOLD     = 0.10   // next ~15%
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION stratify_and_route(scores, care_manager_assignments):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     worklist = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient_score in scores:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         tier = determine_tier(patient_score.score)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         intervention = determine_intervention(patient_score.risk_drivers)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF tier == "HIGH":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Immediate outreach within 48 hours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assigned_cm = lookup care manager for patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             worklist.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 patient_id:     patient_score.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 risk_tier:      "HIGH",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 score:          patient_score.score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 risk_drivers:   patient_score.risk_drivers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 intervention:   intervention,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 assigned_to:    assigned_cm,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 due_date:       today + 2 days,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expires:        today + 14 days   // score is stale after 2 weeks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF tier == "RISING":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Monitor and outreach within 1 week.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             worklist.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 patient_id:     patient_score.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 risk_tier:      "RISING",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 score:          patient_score.score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 risk_drivers:   patient_score.risk_drivers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 intervention:   intervention,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 assigned_to:    assigned_cm,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 due_date:       today + 7 days,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expires:        today + 21 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write worklist to DynamoDB for care management platform consumption.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     batch_write(worklist, table="ed-risk-worklist")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Publish metrics: how many patients in each tier this cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     publish_metrics({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         high_risk_count:   count where tier == "HIGH",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         rising_risk_count: count where tier == "RISING",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_scored:      length of scores
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN worklist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION determine_intervention(risk_drivers):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Map the top risk driver to a recommended intervention type.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is a starting point for the care manager, not a mandate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     primary_driver = risk_drivers[0].feature_name
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF primary_driver contains "pdc" OR primary_driver contains "medication":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "pharmacy_outreach"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF primary_driver contains "missed_appt" OR primary_driver contains "days_since_last_pcp":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "pcp_scheduling"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF primary_driver contains "mental_health":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "behavioral_health_referral"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF primary_driver contains "area_deprivation" OR primary_driver contains "social":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "social_services_referral"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "general_care_management"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.04-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a high-risk patient:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_id": "PAT-2847103",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "score": 0.43,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "score_date": "2026-03-15",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "risk_tier": "HIGH",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "risk_drivers": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "pdc_respiratory_meds", "value": 0.52, "impact": 0.12, "direction": "low adherence increases risk"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "ed_visits_90d", "value": 2, "impact": 0.09, "direction": "recent ED use increases risk"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "days_since_last_pcp", "value": 187, "impact": 0.07, "direction": "care gap increases risk"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "missed_appts_90d", "value": 3, "impact": 0.05, "direction": "disengagement increases risk"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "has_copd", "value": 1, "impact": 0.04, "direction": "chronic condition increases risk"}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "recommended_intervention": "pharmacy_outreach",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "assigned_to": "CM-JONES-042",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "due_date": "2026-03-17",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "model_version": "ed-pred-v2.3"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AUC (discrimination) | 0.72-0.80 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Precision at top 5% | 25-35% (1 in 3-4 flagged patients will have an ED visit) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Recall at top 5% | 15-25% of actual ED visits captured in top 5% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Calibration (Brier score) | 0.04-0.06 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Scoring latency (500K patients) | 15-30 minutes (batch transform) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Feature pipeline runtime | 45-90 minutes (Glue ETL) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end pipeline | Under 2 hours weekly |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per patient per month | ~$0.02 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patients new to the health plan (less than 6 months of history). The model has no behavioral baseline and defaults to demographic-only features, which are weak predictors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Trauma and accidents. These are genuinely unpredictable and should not be in your outcome label, but they inflate your false negative rate if you're measuring against all ED visits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Rapid social changes (job loss, housing loss, domestic violence). These create sudden risk spikes that historical patterns can't anticipate. By the time claims data reflects the change, the ED visit has already happened.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patients who use the ED as primary care by choice (not by necessity). Their utilization pattern is stable and high, not a trajectory you can deflect with outreach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m I'll be direct about what surprised me building these models.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The model itself is the easy part. Getting to AUC 0.75 with XGBoost on claims data takes a competent data scientist about two weeks. Getting the data pipeline reliable, the feature engineering clinically sound, and the operational workflow actually used by care managers takes six months.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The biggest failure mode is not model accuracy. It's intervention capacity. You build a beautiful model, score your population, identify 2,000 high-risk patients, hand the list to a care management team of 15 people, and they can meaningfully engage maybe 200 of them per month. The other 1,800 sit on a list getting stale. Then leadership asks "why aren't we seeing ED reduction?" and the answer is "because we identified the patients but couldn't reach them." Calibrate your thresholds to your capacity, not to your model's discrimination ability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second surprise: claims data lag kills you. A patient fills their last inhaler on March 1. The pharmacy claim arrives in your data warehouse on March 20. Your weekly scoring run picks it up on March 22. The care manager calls on March 25. The patient had an asthma exacerbation and went to the ED on March 15. Your model was right, but the data latency made the prediction arrive after the event. If you can get pharmacy data in near-real-time (some PBMs offer daily feeds), that single improvement can shift your intervention window by 2-3 weeks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The fairness issue is real and uncomfortable. Models trained on historical claims data will flag patients from underserved communities at higher rates because those communities have higher ED utilization. That's not a model bug; it's a reflection of systemic access barriers. The question is what you do with that information. If your intervention is "offer a PCP appointment" but the patient can't get to the clinic, you haven't helped. The best implementations pair the predictive model with a social needs assessment and connect patients to community resources, not just clinical services.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m One more thing: clinician trust takes time. The first time a care manager calls a patient flagged as high-risk and the patient says "I'm fine, I don't know why you're calling me," that care manager will stop trusting the model. You need to set expectations: the model identifies patients with elevated probability, not certainty. A 35% probability means 65% of the time, nothing happens. That's not a model failure. That's how probability works. But it feels like a failure to the person making the call.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real-time scoring with EHR integration.** Instead of weekly batch scoring, trigger a re-score when specific events occur: a missed appointment, a new ED visit, a medication fill gap exceeding 14 days. This requires near-real-time event streaming (Kinesis or MSK) and a hosted model endpoint (SageMaker real-time inference) rather than batch transform. The tradeoff is cost: a real-time endpoint runs continuously, while batch transform runs only during scoring windows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-horizon prediction.** Train separate models for 30-day, 60-day, and 90-day horizons. Shorter horizons are more actionable (less time to intervene) but harder to predict accurately. Longer horizons give more intervention time but lower precision. Present all three scores to care managers and let them prioritize based on urgency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intervention effectiveness feedback loop.** Track which interventions were attempted, which patients were reached, and whether the predicted ED visit occurred. Use this data to build a second model: "Given that we intervened, did it work?" This closes the loop and allows you to estimate the causal impact of your program, not just the predictive accuracy of your model. It also identifies which intervention types work for which risk profiles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.1 (Appointment No-Show Prediction):** Shares feature engineering patterns (utilization history, engagement signals) and the same temporal validation approach
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.3 (Patient Churn / Disenrollment Prediction):** Uses similar disengagement signals but predicts plan departure rather than ED utilization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.5 (30-Day Readmission Risk):** Closely related prediction target; readmission models often share features with ED prediction models
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.6 (Rising Risk Identification):** Extends this recipe's point-in-time scoring to trajectory-based risk detection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.2 (Utilization Pattern Segmentation):** Provides the clustering foundation that can improve ED prediction by identifying distinct utilization archetypes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
